<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet xml:id="sec-9-2-1">
        <title><m>\S 9.2</m>: Properties of Integration</title>

        <exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="8in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that every constant real function is integrable over every interval <m>[a,b]</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="8in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Suppose <m>f</m> is a bounded real function on <m>[a,b]</m>.
Then <m>f</m> is (Riemann) integrable if and only if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, there exists a partition <m>P</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> such that <m>U_{P}(f) - L_{P}(f) \lt \varepsilon</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="8in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Define <m>f: \mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{R}</m> defined via <m>f(x) =x</m>.
Using the tools we currently have at our disposal, prove that <m>f</m> is integrable on <m>[0,1]</m> and compute the value of the integral.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    
                </exercise>

            <exercise workspace="2in">
                <title>Definitions</title>
                
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A function <m>f: A \to \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>increasing</term> if for each pair
                        <m>x,y \in A</m> such that <m>x \lt y</m>, 
                    </p>
                </statement>
                
            </exercise>


				<exercise>
                    <title>Problems</title>
                    <task workspace="8in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                            Prove that if <m>f</m> is a bounded monotonic real function on <m>[a,b]</m>, then <m>f</m> is integrable on <m>[a,b]</m>.
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="8in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                          Prove that each of the following exist.
Do you know the value of any of these integrals knowing what we know now and perhaps some well-known area formulas?
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\int_{1}^{2} x^{2} dx</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\int_{1}^{17}e^{-x}dx</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\int_{0}^{1} \sqrt{1-x^{2}}dx</m>
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      <m>\int_{0}^{1} \sqrt{1+x^{4}}dx</m>
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                     <task workspace="8in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                           Suppose <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are integrable real functions on <m>[a,b]</m> and let <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>.
Prove each of the following:
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      The function <m>cf</m> is integrable on <m>[a,b]</m> and <m>\int_{a}^{b} cf = c\int_{a}^{b}f</m>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      The function <m>f+g</m> is integrable on <m>[a,b]</m> and <m>\int_{a}^{b} (f+g) = \int_{a}^{b} f + \int_{a}^{b} g</m>.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      The function <m>f-g</m> is integrable on <m>[a,b]</m> and <m>\int_{a}^{b} (f-g) = \int_{a}^{b} f - \int_{a}^{b} g</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="8in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                         Find two real function <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> that are integrable on <m>[0,1]</m> such that <m>fg</m> is also integrable on <m>[0,1]</m> but
<md>
  \left(\int_{0}^{1}f\right)\left(\int_{0}^{1} g\right) \neq \int_{0}^{1} fg.
</md>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                    </task>

                    
                </exercise>
                

        </worksheet>
    </article>
</pretext>